The Burris Fullfield II Rifle Scope has a one-piece main tube and eyepiece, Burris envied steel-on-steel adjustment system, and HiLume multi-coatings on every single air to glass lens surface. The Burris FullField-II Scope is even more forgiving for eye position, is a little shorter, and a good bit lighter. The magnification ring and eyepiece have been made into one solid unit requiring only two seals rather than three. To change magnification, simply turn the entire eyepiece. Burris Fullfield 2 Scope eliminated most of the potential leak paths in the eyepiece/power ring area and sealed the remainder with special quad seals instead of O-rings. The adjustment system has been moved to improve mounting options and the European-style adjustable eyepiece requires no locking mechanism. The Ballistic Plex reticle has a lower vertical crosshair with small ballistic lines that automatically compensate for bullet drop from 100 to 500 yards for many common cartridges. The Burris Fullfield-2 Riflescope is lighter, better sealed, and has a relocated adjustment system compared to the original Burris Fullfield.

The Burris Landmark Binoculars combine light weight, fully coated lenses and water resistant, fogproof construction. Each scope is filled and purged at least 24 times with high quality, laboratory grade dry nitrogen. Each nitrogen cycle absorbs airborne and residual surface moisture that is evacuated from the scope. Burris uses specially made quad seals to provide double insurance against leakage.
Fog proof: The nitrogen contained in the scope is of high quality (ultra dry, laboratory grade nitrogen), ultra pure and ultra clean. To be sure that all airborne moisture and surfaces moisture within a scope is evacuated, testing consists of 24 cycles of pressurizing the scope and then subjecting it to a vacuum. Ballistic Plex reticle - with a basic crosshair reticle, calculating hold-over is a mix of art, science and just plain luck, which is why Burris developed the Ballistic Plex reticle. The key is the copyrighted lower vertical crosshair. With most common hunting cartridges, a shooter can use the reticle to compensate for bullet drop and aim dead-on at targets from 100 to 500 yards out. The need for hold-over guesstimation is eliminated. Using it is simple. Start by sighting-in your rifle at 100 or 200 yards at your scope's highest magnification. title: For Sale/Trade:  VZ-58 Parts Kit with Czech D-Technik Receiver 7.62x39
postcontent:
I bought this kit and receiver a while ago with intentions of building it. From what I understand, the barrel was pressed part way into the receiver and it was oversized. It will need to be pressed out of the receiver and turned down.

The receiver, when available, sold for $350. It is made in the Czech Republic and is superior to the currently available U.S. made receivers. The parts kits available now are selling for around $300. I realize there is a little extra work involved in pressing the barrel out, so my trade value for this set is $550-$600.

This will require machine and rifle building skills to complete. Please do not buy this if you have not built a rifle before.

All the parts required to build a complete rifle are included. To complete the rifle, you will need to:
-Press barrel out, turn down, press back in. Drill and press barrel pin.
-Rivet trigger guard in.
-Modify trigger group or buy a new semi U.S. group.
-Permanantly attach the included muzzle brake to bring the length to the legal requirement.
-Paint

Here is a website that details the steps involved in building a VZ-58:
http://50ae.net/vz58-2/

And another tutorial, with a U.S. made receiver: http://www.projectguns.com/vz581.html
